        // This logic is derived from the observation that if p[i] = N, then min(p[i], p[j]) = p[j] for all j!=i.
        // So max_{j!=i} (min(p[i], p[j])) = max_{j!=i} (p[j]) = N-1.
        // If p[i] < N, then there is some p[k] > p[i].
        // For such k, min(p[i], p[k]) = p[i].
        // For any j such that p[j] < p[i], min(p[i], p[j]) = p[j].
        // So max_{j!=i} (min(p[i], p[j])) will be p[i] itself.
        // The only exception is when p[i] is N.
        if (max_val_in_row == n - 1) {
